Yucca elephantipes

   [10967.jpg]
    Authority   Regel
      Family    Liliopsida:Liliidae:Asparagales:Agavaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names Yucca, spineless yucca
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 10967

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A small, upright or decumbent, evergreen
   tree that radiates thick, rigid lanceolate leaves from a
   rigid, branching trunk, with large panicles of white
   flowers. USES Whole flowers or perianth only are eaten in
   cooked salads or soups, with eggs, or fried in butter. The
   flowers are rich in vitamin C. The tender leaf bases are
   rich in calcium and can be eaten. The leaves also yields a
   fiber used for twine, cloth, and baskets. Used as hedge,
   garden ornament and for terracing in coffee plantations.
   GROWING PERIOD Perennial. First harvest can be taken 2-3
   years after cuttings. COMMON NAMES Itabo, Flor de itabo,
   Cogollo de itabo, Izote, Palmita, Ozote, Spanish
   bayonnette. FURTHER INF Itabo is native of Mexico or
   Central America. It occurs naturally in very dry areas but
   tolerates heavy rainfall if drainage is good.

   Sources
   SOURCES (Y. elephantipes Regel.)
   Roecklein J 1987 pp 491 [USE, DRA, TEXT]
   Duke J 1975 pp 31 [PH, RAIN, TEMP]
   Martin F 1984 pp 164-165 [TEMP, RAIN, PHO, DRA, TEXT, USE]

